Sandy Berger, a former national security leader, has passed away. He served in the State Department under President Carter and was President Clinton's National Security Advisor. Berger played a crucial role in strengthening American leadership in an uncertain world. His legacy includes a peaceful Balkans, a strong alliance with Japan, and deeper relationships with India and China. He also made significant contributions as a private citizen, helping the world respond to crises and feed the hungry. Berger's passion, wisdom, and good humor are fondly remembered within the National Security Council, where those he mentored continue his work. President Obama personally benefited from Berger's advice and counsel. The President expresses gratitude to Berger and extends condolences to his family, including his wife, children, and grandchildren. The President acknowledges that America is stronger because of Berger's service.